article.headline: Griffith scores 20 to lead Sacramento
article.linkText: Monarchs take advantage of 28 LA turnovers in win
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Yolanda Griffith's effort Thursday
night can only help in her bid to make the United States Olympic
basketball team.

The 6-foot-3 Griffith, widely rumored to be the likely final
addition to the U.S. squad, had 20 points and seven rebounds and
completely outplayed Olympian Lisa Leslie in the Sacramento
Monarchs' 68-51 win over the Los Angeles Sparks.

Tangela Smith added 13 points and nine rebounds, including the
1,000th rebound of her career, for the Monarchs (2-3), who recorded
their largest margin of victory over the two-time WNBA champions.

Leslie, who teamed with Griffith on the 2000 Olympic team,
scored just four points before fouling out with 56.6 seconds
remaining.

Mwadi Mabika had 11 points to lead the Sparks (3-3), who shot
just 25 percent from the field (7-of-28) in the second half.

"This is the way we should be playing," said Griffith, who
made 6-of-8 shots from the field and 8-of-10 from the free-throw
line in 33 minutes for Sacramento. "Normally the (second half) is
a little bit of a let down for us, but we came out focused. If we
couldn't score, we made sure they couldn't score."

The Monarchs made sure Leslie couldn't score, though the 2001
league MVP hardly seemed aggressive or motivated. She had just
seven field-goal attempts in 30 minutes, making only two, and had
eight turnovers.

"This is probably the worst game I've ever had," Leslie said.
"What did I have, four offensive fouls? It was just really
frustrating for me in every aspect."

Los Angeles looked vulnerable even before Leslie picked up her
second and third fouls barely two minutes into the second half. The
Sparks led 33-31 at halftime, but Leslie had scored just two points
and was 1-of-5 from the field.

Griffith, who scored 11 points in the first half, made
back-to-back baskets to cut the Sparks' advantage to 35-34 four
minutes into the second half. When Smith converted a three-point
play with just over 13 minutes remaining, the Monarchs led 40-39.
They wouldn't trail again.

"The defensive effort was the key," Monarchs coach John
Whisenant said. "If we defend, it creates some offense for us, and
that's a major key for this basketball team."

Sacramento gradually increased its lead with bench contributions
from guards Kara Lawson (10 points) and Ruthie Bolton (five points,
four rebounds).

The Sparks were helped by their bench as well. Forward Tamika
Whitmore had nine points and Laura Macchi added six.

"We're not fully committed to the game," Sparks coach Michael
Cooper said. "We're not playing hard in the game. The little
adjustments we as coaches can make are minimal. I think it's the
players wanting to get excited about the game."
